               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420509-name-111" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-111" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-111" type="surname" value="MADDOX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-111" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE MADDOX</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a Thames police-inspector. On the morn<lb></lb>ing of the 10th of April, I was at the same wharf at Whitefriars, as I men<lb></lb>tioned in the last case—I saw the prisoner come there about ten o'clock, or a quarter-past ten—I saw him get up and lean on his stomach, on the side of the same barge of coals—he pulled a coal out of the barge, which weighed about 14lbs., and put it into a tin can—I took him into custody, with the coal and the can.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420509-name-112" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-112" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-112" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420509-name-112" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS THOMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. George Hall Pownall. The barge did not belong to him, but the coals did—this coal is about the same quality as was in the barge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> Another boy who was with me took the coals; the can laid nearest to me; the gentleman laid hold of me, and took me to the station; he detained me, but let him go; I never touched the coals.</p>
